cher context. But this might happen many times per session (each commit triggers condensation). The user said \\\"should only happen once\\\" which makes sense.\\n\\n3. **The \\\"only once\\\" constraint**: Generate the title once, don't regenerate on every commit. \\n\\nSo I need a way to track whether the title was already generated. Using a cheap model like Haiku to generate just a title and description from the prompt could be fast enough to do synchronously at TurnStart.\\n\\nNow I'm realizing the lifecycle issue - each hook runs in its own process that exits afterward, so I can't rely on process state to track whether we've already generated a title.\\n\\nThe user might be thinking the agent itself could generate the title, but that's not how the CLI works since it's a separate binary. I think the best approach is to generate the title synchronously at TurnStart using a cheap model with a simple prompt, which should complete in a second or two. If it fails or times out, I can fall back to extracting from the prompt directly. And I'd only generate it once when creating a new trail, not on subsequent turns. The prompt alone is usually sufficient for a good title, Haiku is fast enough at 1-2 seconds to not noticeably delay the hook, and it only runs once per trail with no concurrency issues. But I'm realizing the TurnStart hook runs synchronously before the agent processes the prompt through the CLI's UserPromptSubmit hook, so even a couple seconds could impact the user experience—I should keep this generation fast and lightweight.\\n\\nNow I'm thinking about whether the Claude CLI binary would even be available in all environments, especially if someone's using a different agent like Gemini. The CLI has a graceful fallback if it's not installed, but for the trail title I'd ideally want to use whatever model is cheapest and fastest from the active agent. The user suggested using the agent's own API access, but the CLI doesn't have direct API access—it just shells